      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Various artists: 'The Wassoulou Sound: Women of Mali'</p>
        <p>Stern's Africa STCD 1035; CD and cassette (available from Stern's Music, 598 Broadway, New York, N.Y. 10012)</p>
        <p>.</p>
        <p>A folk style takes steps toward pop on this sampler of five singers -- Sali Sidibe, Oumou Sangare, Coumba Sidibe, Dienaba Diakite and Kagbe Sidibe -- from the Wassoulou region of southern Mali. Women there have a tradition of singing about contemporary events and everyday situations, and lately they have been carrying their songs into recording studios.</p>
        <p>The melodies can be short and catchy or long and intricately inflected, with the lead singer's voice answered by girlish choruses or by an Arab-tinged violin; the rolling, rippling backup might include traditional Malian instruments, an electric guitar, a cheap drum machine or opulent synthesizers.</p>
        <p>Coumba Sidibe, an established star in Mali, has the most electrified arrangements behind her raw, incantatory voice; Sali Sidibe, backed by Malian xylophone and by kamal ngoni, a six-stringed gut-strung harp, sounds closer to traditional music, while Oumou Sangare croons above a jaunty mixture of kamal ngoni and Western bass and drums. Unfortunately, the album has sketchy notes and lacks translations of the lyrics.</p>
      </block>
